topic.title: Eye Observation Monitor

body.p:
PMCSJIRAJIRA- Q8530-430
MRPC Command ID: 0x10

See PCIe Eye Capture for an overview of the EOM tool. EOM scans a matrix of positions on an eye capture map and reports the error found at each point. This can be done per-lane with multiple lanes being captured simultaneously. The resolution of the capture can be as high as 511x64.
In order to collect EOM data, this MRPC command requires three parameters:

li.p: Define the time dimension (x_start, x_end, x_step)
Define the voltage dimension (y_start, y_end, y_step)
Define the dwell time - the time spent on each capture point (time_in_ms)

body.p: EOM is performed as a scan starting at x_start / y_start and moving across the x-axis by x_step until x_end. At this point, the the Y coordinate is incremented by y_step and the X position returns to x_start and the scan begins again. This is repeated until the position has reached x_end and y_end.
There are three sub commands for EOM operation:
For every EOM MRPC command issued, the EOM handler will check whether the sub command is valid.
For each EOM sub command, the sub command status can be got from the MRPC output fields to determine whether the execution is successful.

entry.p: Execution of sub command is success
Data is not ready for EOM operation is in progress
Input parameter for EOM is invalid
Start EOM sub command has been rejected for previous EOM operation is not finished

topic.title: EOM - Start EOM Sub-Command

body.p: Start EOM sub-command is used to initiate an EOM operation. EOM operation can only be started when there is no previous EOM operation on-going.
Set to 0x0 for Start EOM Sub-Command.
Select the physical lane which will perform the EOM operation.
Specifies start coordinate of the X axis. The range of time in X axis is (0, 63).
Specifies start coordinate of the Y axis. The range of voltage in Y axis is (-255, 255).
Specifies end coordinate of the X axis. The range of time in X axis is (0, 63). The x_end must be greater than or equal to x_start.
Specifies end coordinate of the Y axis. The range of voltage in Y axis is (-255, 255). The x_end must be greater than or equal to x_start.
Step granularity on X axis.
Step granularity on Y axis.
Specify the EOM sampling time for each sampling step. The unit time is ms.

p.b: The output data of Start EOM Sub-Command gives the command execution status.

body.p: This field indicates whether the execution Start EOM Sub-Command is success or not:

ul.li: 0x00000000 - Execution of sub command is success
0x00000002 - Input parameter for EOM is invalid
0x00000003 - Start EOM sub command has been rejected for previous EOM operation is not finished

topic.title: EOM - Fetch Data Sub-Command

body.p: Fetch Data sub-command is used to fetch the EOM sampling data.
Set to 0x1 for Fetch Data Sub-Command.

p.b: The output data of Fetch Data Sub-Command outputs the EOM Data Frame.

body.p: During the EOM operation, all the selected physical lanes by Start EOM sub command will start each sampling step at the same time. There is internal buffer in Switchtec chip to hold the EOM data during the entire EOM process. Depends the selected physical lane count and the sampling pixel count determined by X/Y range, the internal buffer maybe cannot hold all the pixels at one time. Under this situation, when the first n pixels of all selected physical lanes has finished and there is no enough memory to hold another EOM step, the EOM operation will suspend and an MRPC event will be sent to host to trigger the Fetch Data operation. After host read back the EOM data, the internal buffer will be free and the EOM opeation will be resumed.

note.p: For each Fetch Data Sub-Command, there is only 1KB 1 kB MRPC output buffer, which cannot hold the entire internal buffer. So multiple Fetch Data Sub-Command maybe needed to read all the EOM data of the internal buffer. For every Fetch Data process, the 1KB 1 kB MRPC output buffer can only hold 62 pixel data after subtracted the header fields, and it can at least hold the entire pending data of 1 lane. If the MRPC output buffer can hold entire pending data of multiple lanes, the lane_mask will has the bits set for corresponding lanes. If the spare space of the MRPC output buffer can only hold partial data of some lane, then the spare space will not be used and the data of that lane should be read in next round of Fetch Data process.

entry.p: logical lane (m - 1) pixel n - 1: sample count

body.p: This field indicates whether the execution Fetch Data Sub-Command is success or not:

ul.li: 0x00000000 - Execution of sub command is success
0x00000002 - Fetch Data is invalid due to no EOM operation is on-going

p.note: EOM data frame is only valid when the sub-command status of Fetch Data sub-command is success.

body.p: Each bit in the lane mask indicates the physical lane number of the pixel data .
Indicates the X coordinate of pixel 0 for current EOM Data frame.
Indicates the Y coordinate of pixel 0 for current EOM Data frame.
Indicates how many pixel count for current lane. All physical lanes corresponding to the lane_mask setting bits will have the same count of data_count pixel data.
Bit[0]: cmd_complete flag, when set, indicates the entire EOM operation is finished.

Bit[1]: data_more flag, indicates whether all EOM data for current EOM internal buffer has been read. When this bit is cleared during Fetch Data process, it means all the data frames for current EOM internal buffer has been fetched. If cmd_complete is not set, user needs to wait until the next internal buffer is ready.
Bit[23:2]: Reserved
The sampling error count for current pixel point.
The sample count for current pixel point.

note.p: 1. The logical lane0 corresponding to the lowest setting bit in the lane_mask and the logical lane (m - 1) corresponding to the highest setting bit in the lane_mask.

2. With the data_count and (x_start, y_start), the mapping of pixel data(0 ~ data_count) to (x, y) coordinates of each physical lane can be confirmed. Take the example of both x_step and y_step set to 1, the mapping is:
pixel 0, pixel 1, ..., pixel (n - 1) -> (x_start, y_start), (x_start + 1, y_start), ... (x_end, y_start), (x_start, y_start + 1), ...

topic.title: EOM - Cancel EOM Sub-Command

body.p: The Cancel EOM sub command is used to cancel the on-going EOM operation. After this sub command has been issued, all the on-going EOM data frame will be discarded.
Set to 0x2 for Cancel EOM Sub-Command.

p.b: The output data of Cancel EOM Sub-Command gives the command execution status.

body.p: This field indicates whether the execution Start EOM Sub-Command is success or not:

ul.li: 0x00000000 - Execution of sub command is success
0x00000002 - There is no EOM operation on-going

topic.title: EOM - Set Data Mode

body.p: The Set Data Mode EOM sub command is used to set the how the pixel data will be stored in the internal buffer and transferred by the Fetch Data Sub command. This command can only be issued when there is no EOM command on-going.
Set to 0x3 for Set Data Mode Sub-Command.
0: The raw payload mode, each pixel data will have two UINT64 data(error count, sample count).
1: The error ratio mode, each pixel data will only store UINT16 data(error count * 65536 / sample count). The float error ratio can be got by divide 65536 upper layer.

p.b: The output data of Cancel EOM Sub-Command gives the command execution status.

body.p: This field indicates whether the execution Start EOM Sub-Command is success or not:

ul.li: 0x00000000 - Execution of sub command is success

topic.title: EOM - Execution Flows (INTERNAL)

body.p: The following picture gives the EOM execution flow.

li.p: FW starts a new thread to perform the EOM requests from MRPC CMD.

ol.li: MRPC user issues Start EOM sub command to initiate the EOM operation request.
MRPC handler will check the Start EOM sub command and parameters, and send the valid EOM request to the EOM thread, or just reject the invalid EOM request.
The EOM thread calls HW interface to start the per-lane EOM by pixel, and save the EOM result into a internal EOM buffer.
Once there is any data available in the local EOM buffer to transfer, FW will notify the host to get data by a synchronous MRPC event.

li.p: Once the synchronous MRPC notify event is received, user can send EOM_MRPC_SUB_CMD_FETCH_DATA to check the command status, such as data_more bit and cmd_complete bit, and get output data.
1) If data_more equals to 1, user can try this command for more data.
2) If cmd_complete equals to 1, the eom operation is all finished.
User can try EOM_MRPC_SUB_CMD_FETCH_DATA to check the command status at any time after the EOM_MRPC_SUB_CMD_START_EOM, without the MRPC notify event.
